#: src/pages/docs/concepts/GlossaryPage.tsx:138
msgid "The most recent valid frame a tile has received, held on screen whenever its source hiccups so a brief dropout is invisible. Tiles escalate from holding the last-good frame to a reconnect indicator and finally a \"no signal\" slate if the source stays away."
msgstr ""

#: src/pages/docs/concepts/GlossaryPage.tsx:185
msgid "The MPEG transport stream container used throughout broadcast: fixed 188-byte packets multiplexing video, audio, subtitles, and data on numbered PIDs, designed to stay decodable through noise and joins. Carried over UDP/multicast in facilities and inside SRT across the internet."
msgstr ""

#: src/pages/docs/concepts/TransportsPage.tsx:175
msgid "The MPEG transport stream is the container broadcast infrastructure speaks: a self-synchronizing packet format that multiplexes video, audio, subtitles, and data on numbered PIDs. Sent over UDP — usually to a multicast group so one sender feeds any number of receivers on the network — it is the classic in-facility distribution method, with latency well under a second."
msgstr ""

#: src/pages/docs/concepts/GlossaryPage.tsx:361
msgid "The open standard for playing a WebRTC stream from a browser: the player POSTs an SDP offer to a single URL and receives the answer, then media flows over the peer connection. Multiview serves WHEP for <0>webrtc</0> outputs and for the sub-second in-app live preview."
msgstr ""

#: src/pages/docs/concepts/GlossaryPage.tsx:373
msgid "The open standard for publishing a WebRTC stream into a server: a browser or encoder POSTs an SDP offer to a single URL and receives the answer, then sends media over the peer connection. A Multiview <0>webrtc</0> source is published to over WHIP."
msgstr ""

#: src/pages/docs/ConfigPage.tsx:376
msgid "The optional <0>[webrtc]</0> section tunes the built-in WebRTC endpoint that serves WHEP playback and the live preview and accepts WHIP publishing. Most deployments need none of it: browsers on the same network reach the server directly. When viewers or publishers sit behind strict NATs or firewalls, add one or more <1>[[webrtc.ice_servers]]</1> entries pointing at a STUN and/or TURN server so the connection can be relayed."
msgstr ""

